  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 Enteral nutrition: a double-edged sword requiring sharp clinical judgment.**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe provided answer correctly identifies all listed options (A, B, C, D) as potential complications of enteral nutrition. This highlights that while often considered safer, enteral nutrition carries significant risks if not managed judiciously, sometimes even exceeding those of well-managed parenteral nutrition.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nVomiting and aspiration (B) are common, especially with gastrostomy tubes and altered gastric motility, preventable by head elevation and careful feeding protocols. Hyperosmolar, nonketotic coma (A) can result from rapid administration of hypertonic formulas into the small bowel, leading to massive diarrhea, fluid loss, and overwhelming carbohydrate absorption. Severe, unremitting diarrhea, often triggered by hypertonic feeds, can compromise intestinal integrity, leading to necrosis, pneumatosis cystoides intestinalis (C), and ultimately perforation and peritonitis (D). All these complications underscore the need for meticulous care in initiating and maintaining enteral nutrition.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nAll options A, B, C, and D are correct complications of enteral nutrition as detailed in the discussion. Therefore, there are no incorrect options to address.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Complication Type | Mechanism | Prevention |\n|---|---|---|\n| **Aspiration** | Gastric stasis, improper tube placement, rapid infusion | Head elevation, slow infusion, post-pyloric feeding, monitoring gastric residuals |\n| **Metabolic (Hyperosmolar Coma)** | Rapid hypertonic formula administration, fluid imbalance, massive diarrhea | Gradual increase in tonicity/volume, careful monitoring of electrolytes and glucose |\n| **Gastrointestinal (Diarrhea, Pneumatosis, Perforation)** | Rapid hypertonic infusion, severe unremitting diarrhea, intestinal ischemia | Gradual initiation, appropriate formula selection, careful monitoring of bowel function |\n| **Tube-related** | Dislodgement, obstruction, infection at insertion site | Proper tube securement, regular flushing, meticulous site care |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Enteral nutrition, though natural, demands vigilance; complications can be severe.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nPneumatosis cystoides intestinalis would appear as intramural gas (air within the bowel wall) on abdominal X-ray or CT scan. Perforation and peritonitis would manifest as free air under the diaphragm on an upright chest X-ray or free fluid and air in the abdomen on CT, often requiring surgical exploration and repair in the OR.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nASPEN/SCCM Guidelines for the Provision and Assessment of Nutrition Support Therapy in the Adult Critically Ill Patient (2016) recommend careful initiation and monitoring of enteral nutrition to prevent complications.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | Hyperosmolar, nonketotic coma. | ❌ Incorrect |\n| B | Vomiting and aspiration. | ❌ Incorrect |\n| C | Pneumatosis cystoides intestinalis. | ❌ Incorrect |\n| D | Perforation and peritonitis. | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: ABCD) DISCUSSION: It is not necessarily true that enteral nutrition is safer than parenteral nutrition, an** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Hard** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: 644827546-General-Surgery-MCQ.txt**\n",
