  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 For diabetics, symptomatic gallstones mean prompt elective surgery, not watchful waiting!**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nOption E is correct because diabetes patients with symptomatic gallstones are at a significantly higher risk for severe complications like acute cholecystitis and gallbladder necrosis. Elective cholecystectomy in this population prevents these complications and avoids the substantially increased mortality associated with emergency surgery.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nDiabetic patients, particularly those with type II, exhibit a higher prevalence of gallstones, often linked to dyslipoproteinemia. While prophylactic cholecystectomy for asymptomatic stones is not justified due to comparable risks of surgery versus complications, the development of symptoms necessitates prompt intervention. Emergency operations in diabetic patients with comorbidities, such as coronary artery disease, carry a substantial added mortality risk. Therefore, prompt elective cholecystectomy is the preferred strategy to mitigate the progression to acute, life-threatening complications and the higher operative risk of an emergent procedure.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption A (Incorrect): Gallstones occur with *greater* frequency in diabetes patients, not the same frequency, often due to dyslipoproteinemia.\nOption B (Incorrect): Prophylactic cholecystectomy for asymptomatic gallstones in diabetes patients is *not* indicated, as the risk of the procedure is comparable to the risk of complications from the gallstones themselves.\nOption C (Incorrect): Diabetes patients with symptomatic gallstones should undergo surgical management (cholecystectomy), not nonoperative treatment, due to their increased risk of severe complications and higher mortality with emergency surgery.\nOption D (Incorrect): There is no established causal relationship between the presence of diabetes, gallstones, and an increased risk of pancreatic cancer.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Feature | Asymptomatic Gallstones (Diabetic) | Symptomatic Gallstones (Diabetic) | Asymptomatic Gallstones (Non-Diabetic) | Symptomatic Gallstones (Non-Diabetic) |\n|---|---|---|---|---|\n| Prevalence | Increased | Increased | General population rate | General population rate |\n| Prophylactic Cholecystectomy | Not recommended | Recommended (prompt elective) | Not recommended | Recommended (elective) |\n| Risk of Complications | Low (if asymptomatic) | High (acute cholecystitis, gangrene) | Low (if asymptomatic) | Moderate to High |\n| Operative Risk | Moderate (elective) | High (emergency) | Low (elective) | Moderate to High |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Symptomatic diabetic gallstones = prompt elective cholecystectomy to avoid emergency risks.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nOn ultrasound, gallstones (cholelithiasis) would be visible, and in acute cholecystitis, findings like gallbladder wall thickening, pericholecystic fluid, and a sonographic Murphy's sign may be present. Intraoperatively, the gallbladder may appear acutely inflamed, edematous, or even gangrenous, especially in diabetic patients.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nSAGES Clinical Practice Guidelines on the Management of Gallstones (e.g., 2010, updated periodically) recommend cholecystectomy for symptomatic gallstones and do not support prophylactic cholecystectomy for asymptomatic stones in diabetic patients.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | Gallstones occur with the same frequency in diabetes patients as in the hea | ❌ Incorrect |\n| B | The presence of gallstones, regardless of the presence of symptoms, is an i | ❌ Incorrect |\n| C | Diabetes patients with gallstones and chronic biliary pain should be manage | ❌ Incorrect |\n| D | The presence of diabetes and gallstones places the patient at high risk for | ❌ Incorrect |\n| E | Diabetes patients with symptomatic gallstones should have prompt elective c | ✅ Correct |\n\n**✅ Answer: E) DISCUSSION: Gallstones have been found to be very prevalent in patients with type II (non–insulin-de** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: 644827546-General-Surgery-MCQ.txt**\n",
