  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 Ketorolac: great pain relief, but mind the kidneys and the clock!**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe verdict is ACCEPT. Ketorolac is correctly identified as a nonsteroidal anti-inflammatory drug (NSAID) approved for multiple administration routes (A) and is known to cause renal dysfunction (C). These are fundamental characteristics of this commonly used analgesic.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nKetorolac, as an NSAID, exerts its analgesic effect by inhibiting cyclooxygenase (COX) enzymes, thereby reducing prostaglandin synthesis. This mechanism is effective for pain relief but also underlies its potential side effects. Renal dysfunction, a critical concern, arises from the inhibition of renal prostaglandins, which are vital for maintaining renal blood flow and glomerular filtration, especially in compromised states. Its availability in intravenous, intramuscular, and oral forms makes it a versatile option for acute pain management.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption B (Incorrect): Ketorolac has a strict recommendation against prolonged use, typically not exceeding 5 consecutive days, due to increased risk of adverse effects like GI bleeding and renal dysfunction.\nOption D (Incorrect): Contrary to decreasing blood loss, ketorolac, like other NSAIDs, inhibits platelet aggregation, which can actually *increase* surgical bleeding.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Feature | Ketorolac (NSAID) | Opioids | Acetaminophen |\n|---|---|---|---|\n| Mechanism | COX inhibition (prostaglandin synthesis) | Mu-opioid receptor agonism | Central COX inhibition, other mechanisms |\n| Key Side Effects | Renal dysfunction, GI bleed, platelet dysfunction | Respiratory depression, constipation, addiction | Hepatotoxicity (high dose), rare skin reactions |\n| Post-op Use | Short-term (max 5 days) for moderate pain, opioid-sparing | Moderate to severe pain, short or long-term | Mild to moderate pain, opioid-sparing |\n| Bleeding Risk | Increased (platelet inhibition) | No direct effect | Minimal |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Ketorolac is a potent NSAID; remember its 5-day limit and renal/bleeding risks.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nNot applicable.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nAmerican Society of Anesthesiologists (ASA) Practice Guidelines for Acute Pain Management in the Perioperative Setting (2012, updated 2023) recommend multimodal analgesia including NSAIDs, but caution against prolonged use and in patients with renal impairment.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | Is a nonsteroidal anti-inﬂammatory drug (NSAID) approved for intravenous, i | ❌ Incorrect |\n| B | Can be used indeﬁnitely for postoperative analgesia. | ❌ Incorrect |\n| C | Can cause renal dysfunction. | ❌ Incorrect |\n| D | May decrease surgical blood loss. | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: AC) DISCUSSION: Ketorolac tromethamine, an NSAID, is approved by the FDA for intravenous, intramuscular,** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: 644827546-General-Surgery-MCQ.txt**\n",
