  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 Cells stand tall and move with their three filament friends!**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe cytoskeleton, a dynamic network within the cytoplasm, is indeed dependent on all three major types of protein filaments: microtubules, intermediate filaments, and actin filaments. These structures collectively provide the cell with its shape, mechanical strength, and the ability to move and transport intracellular components.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nThe cytoskeleton is a complex and essential cellular framework. Actin filaments (microfilaments) are the thinnest, involved in cell shape, locomotion, and muscle contraction. Intermediate filaments provide mechanical strength and resistance to stress, forming a stable network. Microtubules are the largest, crucial for maintaining cell shape, intracellular transport (acting as tracks for motor proteins), and chromosome segregation during cell division. Their combined functions are vital for cellular integrity and activity.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption D (Incorrect): \"None of the above\" is incorrect because the cytoskeleton is fundamentally composed of and dependent on actin filaments, intermediate filaments, and microtubules for its diverse functions.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Filament Type | Diameter (nm) | Primary Function | Key Proteins |\n|---|---|---|---|\n| Actin Filaments (Microfilaments) | 7 | Cell shape, locomotion, muscle contraction, cytokinesis | Actin |\n| Intermediate Filaments | 8-12 | Mechanical strength, nuclear lamina, cell-cell/cell-matrix junctions | Keratins, Vimentin, Lamins, Neurofilaments |\n| Microtubules | 25 | Cell shape, intracellular transport, cilia/flagella movement, chromosome segregation | Alpha- and Beta-tubulin |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: The cytoskeleton's three pillars are actin, intermediate, and microtubules.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nThis question pertains to fundamental cell biology and does not have direct imaging or intraoperative relevance.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nN/A. This is a basic science question, not related to clinical guidelines.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | Microtubules | ❌ Incorrect |\n| B | Intermediate ﬁlaments | ❌ Incorrect |\n| C | Actin ﬁlaments | ❌ Incorrect |\n| D | None of the above | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: a, b, c) The cytoskeleton is a collection of ﬁlamentous protein structures that allow cells to assume and mai** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Easy** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: 644827546-General-Surgery-MCQ.txt**\n",
