  "answer": "a, b, c) Channel blockade is an important mechanism of action for toxins and some therapeutic agents. The deadly toxin of the puﬀer ﬁsh, tetrodotoxin, acts by blocking the Na+ channels that are responsible for the conduction of nerve impulse. The diuretic, amiloride, acts by blocking the Na+ channels that inhabit the apical membrane of the epithelial cells of the distal nephron. Local anesthetics such xylocaine also act by blocking ion channels.",
