  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 Don't get tangled in thrombolytic half-lives; focus on their unique traits!**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe correct answer highlights crucial distinctions among thrombolytic agents. Streptokinase, being a bacterial protein, is antigenic and significantly cheaper, while tissue plasminogen activator (TPA) and urokinase act directly on plasminogen without forming an intermediate complex.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nStreptokinase, derived from group C beta-hemolytic streptococci, is a bacterial protein, making it highly antigenic in humans and prone to causing allergic reactions and even serum sickness. In contrast, urokinase and TPA, produced through recombinant DNA technology, are non-antigenic. Mechanistically, streptokinase forms an intermediate streptokinase-plasmin complex to activate plasminogen, whereas urokinase and TPA directly convert plasminogen to plasmin. Despite these differences in origin, antigenicity, and mechanism, the overall efficacy of these agents in achieving thrombolysis is comparable, though streptokinase remains markedly less expensive.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption C (Incorrect): The half-lives of streptokinase, urokinase, and TPA are all less than 30 minutes, not exceeding 30 minutes as stated in the option. This makes the statement false.\nOption A (Correct): Streptokinase is indeed a bacterial protein, antigenic in humans, and can cause allergic reactions in a significant percentage of cases.\nOption B (Correct): TPA acts directly on plasminogen to form plasmin, without requiring an intermediate drug-plasmin complex, unlike streptokinase.\nOption D (Correct): Streptokinase is significantly more affordable than either urokinase or TPA.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Feature | Streptokinase | Urokinase | TPA (Alteplase) |\n| :--------------- | :------------------------------------------ | :------------------------------------------ | :-------------------------------------------- |\n| **Origin** | Bacterial protein | Human kidney cell culture | Recombinant DNA (human) |\n| **Antigenicity** | High (allergic reactions, serum sickness) | None | None |\n| **Mechanism** | Forms streptokinase-plasmin complex | Direct activation of plasminogen to plasmin | Direct activation of plasminogen to plasmin |\n| **Half-life** | < 30 minutes | < 30 minutes | < 30 minutes |\n| **Cost** | Significantly cheaper | More expensive | Most expensive |\n| **Lytic State** | Greatest | Intermediate | Least |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Antigenicity, mechanism, and cost differentiate thrombolytics, not half-life.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nNo image was provided with the question.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nAHA/ACC Guidelines for the Management of Patients with ST-Elevation Myocardial Infarction (2013) recommend timely reperfusion therapy, including fibrinolysis, for STEMI patients when primary PCI is not available within recommended timeframes.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | Streptokinase is a bacterial protein which is antigenic in humans, resultin | ❌ Incorrect |\n| B | Tissue plasminogen activator acts directly on plasmin without an intermedia | ❌ Incorrect |\n| C | The half-life of urokinase, streptokinase, and TPA all exceed 30 minutes | ❌ Incorrect |\n| D | Streptokinase is signiﬁcantly cheaper than urokinase or TPA | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: a, b, d) Streptokinase is a bacterial protein produced by group C b-hemolytic streptococci. It is therefore a** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: 644827546-General-Surgery-MCQ.txt**\n",
