  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 Low fibrinogen: high bleeding risk. Know your contraindications!**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThis question correctly identifies a critical threshold for fibrinogen levels in patients undergoing fibrinolytic therapy. A serum fibrinogen level below 100 mg/dL significantly increases the risk of bleeding complications, making its monitoring crucial for patient safety.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nFibrinolytic therapy works by breaking down existing clots, but this process also induces a hemostatic defect. The primary mechanism involves hypofibrinogenemia, where reduced fibrinogen levels impair the formation of stable clots. Additionally, fibrin degradation products interfere with fibrin polymerization, and a decrease in clotting factors V and VIII further prolongs clotting time. This combination of factors makes a low fibrinogen level a direct indicator of increased bleeding risk.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption A (Incorrect): While coagulation tests like PT and aPTT are monitored, the explanation explicitly states they do not correlate well with bleeding complications in the context of fibrinolytic therapy. Fibrinogen levels are a more direct and reliable indicator.\nOption C (Incorrect): Recent major surgery (less than 10 days) is a major relative contraindication to *both* systemic and regional fibrinolytic therapy, not just systemic. The risk of bleeding at the surgical site is high regardless of the delivery method.\nOption D (Incorrect): A cerebrovascular event less than two months ago is an absolute contraindication to fibrinolytic therapy. A normal head CT scan does not negate this absolute contraindication due to the inherent risk of intracranial hemorrhage in the setting of recent neurological insult.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Parameter/Condition | Relevance to Fibrinolytic Therapy |\n|:--------------------|:----------------------------------|\n| Serum Fibrinogen < 100 mg/dL | Increased bleeding risk; direct indicator of hemostatic impairment |\n| PT/aPTT Monitoring | Generally poor correlation with bleeding complications |\n| Recent Major Surgery (<10 days) | Major relative contraindication for both systemic and regional therapy |\n| Recent CVA (<2 months) | Absolute contraindication due to high risk of intracranial hemorrhage |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Fibrinogen <100 mg/dL is a critical bleeding risk threshold in fibrinolysis.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nNo image was provided in the question. However, in the context of fibrinolytic therapy, a pre-treatment head CT scan is crucial to rule out intracranial hemorrhage, which is an absolute contraindication.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nAmerican Heart Association/American College of Cardiology (AHA/ACC) Guidelines for the Management of Patients with ST-Elevation Myocardial Infarction (2013) and Pulmonary Embolism (2011) recommend careful patient selection and monitoring for bleeding complications, emphasizing contraindications and the importance of assessing bleeding risk.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | Careful monitoring of prothrombin time and aPTT time are necessary to avoid | ❌ Incorrect |\n| B | A level of serum ﬁbrinogen less than 100 mg/dl is associated with an increa | ✅ Correct |\n| C | Recent (less than 10 days) major surgery is a contraindication to systemic  | ❌ Incorrect |\n| D | A patient with a cerebrovascular event occurring less than two months ago c | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: B) Fibrinolytic therapy induces a hemostatic defect through a combination of factors. Hypoﬁbrinogenemia** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: 644827546-General-Surgery-MCQ.txt**\n",
