  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 For unstable kidneys, slow and steady CAVH wins the race.**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe correct answer is A and B. Continuous arteriovenous hemofiltration (CAVH) is an extracorporeal filtration technique that, as its name suggests, runs continuously. This continuous, slow removal of fluid and solutes is precisely why it is associated with minimal hemodynamic instability, making it suitable for critically ill patients.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nCAVH operates by creating a hydrostatic pressure gradient between indwelling arterial and venous catheters, allowing for continuous removal of extracellular fluid across a synthetic membrane. This sustained, gentle filtration prevents the rapid fluid and solute shifts that can destabilize critically ill patients. The technique's inherent stability is further enhanced by the membrane's design, which avoids complement activation upon contact with blood, contributing to its favorable hemodynamic profile and making it a preferred modality for patients with acute kidney injury and cardiovascular compromise.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption C (Incorrect): While heparinization of the extracorporeal circuit is required to prevent clotting, full systemic heparin anticoagulation is generally not necessary for CAVH, distinguishing it from some other RRT modalities.\nOption D (Incorrect): Fluid balance and serum electrolyte concentrations can be precisely titrated and corrected rapidly, often within a matter of hours, by adjusting the composition and rate of the replacement solution, not several days.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Feature | Continuous Arteriovenous Hemofiltration (CAVH) | Intermittent Hemodialysis (IHD) |\n|---|---|---|\n| **Continuity** | Continuous (24/7) | Intermittent (3-5 hours, 3-4x/week) |\n| **Hemodynamic Stability** | High (slow, gentle removal) | Lower (rapid fluid/solute shifts) |\n| **Anticoagulation** | Circuit heparinization often sufficient | Systemic heparinization often required |\n| **Fluid/Electrolyte Control** | Gradual, precise (hours) | Rapid, less precise (acute shifts) |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: CAVH is continuous and hemodynamically stable, ideal for unstable AKI.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nDuring CAVH access placement, fluoroscopy or ultrasound guidance may be used to ensure proper percutaneous cannulation of the femoral artery and vein, confirming appropriate catheter tip positioning within the vessels to optimize flow and minimize complications.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nKDIGO Clinical Practice Guideline for Acute Kidney Injury (2012) recommends continuous renal replacement therapies (CRRT), including CAVH, for hemodynamically unstable patients with AKI requiring renal replacement therapy.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | The technique runs continuously | ❌ Incorrect |\n| B | It is not associated with the hemodynamic instability | ❌ Incorrect |\n| C | Systemic heparin anticoagulation is necessary | ❌ Incorrect |\n| D | Fluid balance and correcting electrolyte abnormalities takes several days | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: a, b) Continuous arteriovenous hemoﬁltration (CAVH) is an extracorporial ﬁltration technique that removes ** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: 644827546-General-Surgery-MCQ.txt**\n",
