  "difficulty": "Medium",
  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 Feed the kidneys, save the patient; nonoliguric is often less dire.**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThis question correctly identifies that maintaining a positive energy balance is crucial in acute renal failure to reduce catabolism, and that nonoliguric renal failure generally carries a better prognosis. These points are fundamental to the management and understanding of acute kidney injury in critically ill patients.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nMaintaining a positive energy balance through adequate caloric intake, primarily with glucose and lipids, minimizes endogenous protein catabolism. This is vital in acute renal failure as it reduces the generation of urea and the release of potassium, thereby easing the management of uremia and hyperkalemia. Nonoliguric renal failure, characterized by preserved urine output, often indicates less severe renal damage, making fluid and electrolyte management less challenging and reducing the need for renal replacement therapy, leading to a more favorable outcome compared to its oliguric counterpart.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption A (Incorrect): Resting energy expenditure in patients with acute renal failure, especially those with multiorgan failure, is typically significantly *increased* (often 50% above normal), not less, due to the critical illness and inflammatory state.\nOption C (Incorrect): While hyperkalemia is a serious and common abnormality, hypercalcemia is incorrect (hypocalcemia is common), and metabolic alkalosis is incorrect (metabolic acidosis is the expected acid-base derangement in acute renal failure).\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Feature | Oliguric Acute Kidney Injury | Nonoliguric Acute Kidney Injury |\n| :---------------------- | :----------------------------------------- | :-------------------------------------------- |\n| Urine Output            | < 400-500 mL/24h                           | > 500 mL/24h                                  |\n| Prognosis               | Generally worse, higher mortality          | Generally better, often reversible            |\n| Need for RRT            | More frequent                              | Less frequent                                 |\n| Fluid Management        | Often requires strict restriction          | Less restrictive, similar to normal function  |\n| Metabolic Derangements  | More pronounced                            | Less severe                                   |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Positive energy balance mitigates catabolism; nonoliguric AKI often has a better prognosis.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nNo imaging or intraoperative findings are directly relevant to this question.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nKDIGO Clinical Practice Guideline for Acute Kidney Injury (2012) recommends optimizing hemodynamics and avoiding nephrotoxic agents to prevent AKI, and providing adequate nutritional support while managing fluid and electrolyte imbalances.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | Resting energy expenditure will likely be less than would be expected for a | ❌ Incorrect |\n| B | Maintenance of positive energy balance reduces protein catabolism and makes | ❌ Incorrect |\n| C | Expected metabolic abnormalities include hyperkalemia, hypercalcemia, and m | ❌ Incorrect |\n| D | A nonoliguric renal failure is usually associated with a better outcome | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: b, d) In patients with nonoliguric renal failure, treatment may diﬀer little from that required for identi** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: 644827546-General-Surgery-MCQ.txt**\n",
