  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 Hydration isn't one-size-fits-all; tailor fluids to age and size!**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nOptions A and C are correct. A 70-kg man requires approximately 2500 mL/day of maintenance fluid, and fluid calculations for elderly patients are generally reduced due to their decreased tolerance for hypervolemia.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nMaintenance intravenous fluid therapy aims to replace normal daily physiological losses, not pre-existing deficits or ongoing additional losses. Fluid requirements are adjusted based on body weight and total body water (TBW) content. Smaller individuals, such as children, have a higher percentage of TBW relative to their body weight, thus requiring a greater amount of fluid per kilogram. Conversely, elderly patients often have reduced fluid tolerance and are prone to hypervolemia, necessitating a decreased fluid volume.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption B (Incorrect): Normal maintenance IV therapy primarily requires administration of sodium and potassium. Replacement of calcium, phosphate, or magnesium is generally not necessary for short-term maintenance but may be crucial in critically ill patients with specific deficits.\nOption D (Incorrect): A child requires a *greater* amount of maintenance fluid per kilogram than a larger individual because they have a higher total body water percentage relative to their body weight and a higher metabolic rate.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Patient Group | Fluid Requirement (per kg) | Key Electrolytes for Maintenance | Special Considerations |\n|---|---|---|---|\n| Adult (70kg) | ~35 mL/kg/day (2500 mL total) | Na, K | Adjust for cardiac/renal status |\n| Child | Higher than adult/kg | Na, K | Higher TBW percentage, higher metabolic rate |\n| Elderly | Decreased from younger adult | Na, K | Poor tolerance of hypervolemia, cardiac/renal comorbidities |\n| Critically Ill | Highly individualized | Na, K, Ca, Phos, Mg (as needed) | Monitor closely for specific deficits |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Maintenance fluids replace normal losses; adjust for age and body size.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nThis question does not pertain to imaging or intraoperative findings.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nNICE Guideline on Intravenous Fluid Therapy in Adults (2017, updated 2023). Recommends 25-30 mL/kg/day of water, 1 mmol/kg/day of sodium, potassium, and chloride, and 50-100 g/day of glucose.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | The total daily water requirement for a 70-kg man is about 2500\nmL/day | ❌ Incorrect |\n| B | Normal maintenance IV therapy requires administration of sodium,\npotassium, | ❌ Incorrect |\n| C | Fluid volume calculations for elderly patients generally are\ndecreased comp | ❌ Incorrect |\n| D | A child requires a lesser amount of maintenance ﬂuid per kilogram\nthan a la | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: a, c) Maintenance ﬂuid replacement is aimed at replacing ﬂuids normally\nlost during the course of a day. C** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: 644827546-General-Surgery-MCQ.txt**\n",
